	volume = {36},
	abstract = {Male natterjack toads, Bufo calamita, sometimes called to attract females and sometimes behaved as silent satellites, attempting to intercept females attracted by callers. Small males with low intensity calls most frequently adopted the satellite tactic and preferred to parasitize the loudest callers. Because body size and call intensity were highly correlated with male mating success, small males with weak calls were at a reproductive disadvantage, and probably achieved greater success by exploiting the displays of larger, louder males than by calling themselves. The behaviour adopted by individual males in a given situation was predicted by a game theory model which assumed that males used an evolutionarily stable decision rule when choosing between alternative mating tactics. However, the model provided close agreement with observed behaviour only when it assumed that males have imperfect information about the behaviour of competitors. It is concluded that male toads adopt a conditional strategy which depends on their attractiveness to females. By switching between mating tactics appropriately, males maximized expected mating success within the constraint of the information available to them. The decision rule of the model qualitativelycorresponds to a proximate mechanism that males appeared to use when switching between tactics. The model offers insights into the behaviour of other species in which males display in groups to attract females.},
